pullRequest.body:
This PR refactors `tfae_have` in terms of `have`, thus supporting all the syntax that `have` supports. We can now also write:
```lean
example : TFAE [P, Q, R] := by
  tfae_have 1 → 2 := sorry
  tfae_have 2 → 1
  | p => f p
  tfae_have ⟨mp, mpr⟩ : 2 ↔ 3 := sorry
  ...
```
Previously, `tfae_have` exclusively pushed a new goal to the top of the goal list, requiring that the result be proved via tactic.

This PR does not deprecate or remove the "old-style" syntax, but does de-document it. The removal of old-style syntax is done in #11000.

This tees us up for a `tfae` block tactic (#10991, #11003).

See [Zulip](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/287929-mathlib4/topic/tfae_have.201.20.E2.86.92.202.20.3A.3D.20syntax).

---

Can you recycle the `declVal` syntax here?

(Note that I have a very hard time understanding how syntax works, so feel free to expand on why this is a bad idea, for my benefit!)

I think `declVal` is for fully generic declarations, and allows some syntax we don't want (like`where` and termination-proving syntax). Note that `letDecl` is what lean uses for `let` and `have`, which parses only the syntax actually usable by `let`/`have`!

We might indeed want to recreate the rest of `letDecl` to allow patterns and match alts like `let` and `have` do! That could be helpful with proving iffs. (However, we can't literally recycle most of the code, since we demand `num impArrow num` in the middle of everything here...) But doing that would be slightly more involved (I'd need to familiarize myself with how we elaborate `let`s in general), so I'd rather save it for another PR.
Thanks for the explanation: it cleared up some doubts that I did not know that I had!

I wonder if we want to write
```suggestion
  tfae_have 1 → 2 := sorry /- proof of P → Q -/
  tfae_have 2 → 1 := sorry /- proof of Q → P -/
  tfae_have 2 ↔ 3 := by
    sorry /- tactic proof of Q ↔ R -/
```
to make it clear how to use tactic here to the reader

Maybe, but this is the docstring for `tfae_finish`, so I wanted to leave the `tfae_have` parts uncluttered just to demonstrate `tfae_finish`. The demonstration of different `tfae_have` syntax is in the `tfae_have` docstring. But I could adjust it if you think it's clearer. Also note that the tactic syntax is "mathlib have" style, not just `by`:
```lean
tfae_have 1 → 2
· admit
```
Ah, I missed this was for `tfae_finish`.
I assume the `?` here is because we're leaving removing the old syntax to a future PR?

It's there because currently we're consistent with "mathlib have" style syntax, where you can just do that (i.e. leave off `:=` and get a new goal). Did we/are we planning to banish that syntax for `have` as well?
(Though if we're being consistent with `have`, maybe I should really push the `tfae_have 1 -> 2 := f ?a ?b` support as well...)
So, to resolve this: yes, we will leave removing it to a future PR! :)

```suggestion
     replaceMainGoal [arrowGoal?, some mainGoal].reduceOption
```
if you like it!
That's definitely golfed but let me see if we want to push the faithful `have` support commit first, as that would obliterate this! :)

What's the difference between this and the shorter:
```suggestion
syntax impArrow := unicodeSymbol " → " " -> " <|> unicodeSymbol " ← " " <- " <|> unicodeSymbol " ↔ " " <-> "
```

The (unfortunate) reasons for not using the shorter version there are
* `unicodeSymbol` doesn't work in `syntax` (there's no parser alias for `unicodeSymbol(" → "," -> ")`)
* if we try inlining all three but leave it as a `: Parser`, then the syntax quotation matches `` `(impArrow| → ) `` below stop working

If we made a parser alias for `unicodeSymbol`, then all of the parsers following this would also have to be changed to `syntax` (as `ParserDescr`s created by `syntax ... := ...` are not allowed to in `Parser`s)—this might be a good thing, though! However, from what I can see, parser aliases (e.g. `many(p)`) can't take non-parser arguments (such as strings), so it might be difficult to get `unicodeSymbol("u","a") : stx` to work. (Maybe there's a way to work around this somehow, by regarding `"u"` and `"a"` as parsers, extracting the strings from them, and failing otherwise? But I'm not completely sure this makes sense.)

I don't understand at all why things work the way it works, for example the following works too:

```lean
private def impTo : Parser := leading_parser unicodeSymbol " → " " -> "
private def impArrow : Parser := leading_parser
  impTo <|>
  (leading_parser unicodeSymbol " ← " " <- ") <|>
  (unicodeSymbol " ↔ " " <-> ")
```

but any other combination of (not) using `leading_parser` seems to fail.

I suggest that @thorimur 's version seems reasonable to keep as-is.

I think the current consensus is that the mathlib-`have` should not be used inside mathlib anymore, and therefore ideally also not imported (see [docs](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Tactic/Have.html)):

> As a style choice, this [mathlib's `have`] should not be used in mathlib; but is provided for downstream users who preferred the old style.

Maybe it's easiest to just drop the import together with this snippet?

Or is there a reasonable workaround which allows not to import the modified `have` here?

Ah, that's right. :) I eliminated the import and moved the entirety of the old-style version to its own section below.

In parallel to Mathlib `have`, I think we ought to move the old `tfae_have` syntax to its own non-imported file in the PR that migrates Mathlib to the new syntax (#11000); what do you think?

I think it would be better to do this inside the elab and use `Lean.Meta.mkFreshBinderNameForTactic` in order to make the tactic hygienic.

I.e. the binder name should probably only be accessible if `set_option tactic.hygienic false`

Hmm, I'm not sure—`tfae_have` is specifically meant to mimic `have` when the binder name is not provided, which means producing an accessible name like `tfae_2_iff_3` in analogy to producing the accessible name `this`. (Note that this is the same mechanism used by `have` to accomplish that.)

(This is also how it currently behaves, so I'd be wary of breaking it!)
ok that's a fair point!
